From: chipyard-linux-nexys
Subject: [PATCH] lib: sbi: Fix console getchar return value validation

SBI_EXT_0_1_CONSOLE_GETCHAR returns the character value (0-255) or -1
if no character is available. The existing error code range check
[-8, 0] incorrectly rejects valid character return values, causing
"Invalid error NNN" messages and breaking keyboard input when running
Linux via SBI console.

Skip the error code validation for CONSOLE_GETCHAR only.

Applies to: software/firemarshal/boards/prototype/firmware/opensbi
Based on OpenSBI commit: 5ccebf0 (v1.2 era)

---
 lib/sbi/sbi_ecall.c | 8 ++++++--
 1 file changed, 7 insertions(+), 1 deletion(-)

diff --git a/lib/sbi/sbi_ecall.c b/lib/sbi/sbi_ecall.c
index d0f0166..cce4338 100644
--- a/lib/sbi/sbi_ecall.c
+++ b/lib/sbi/sbi_ecall.c
@@ -120,7 +120,13 @@ int sbi_ecall_handler(struct sbi_trap_regs *regs)
 		trap.epc = regs->mepc;
 		sbi_trap_redirect(regs, &trap);
 	} else {
-		if (ret < SBI_LAST_ERR || SBI_SUCCESS < ret) {
+		/*
+		 * SBI_EXT_0_1_CONSOLE_GETCHAR is special: it returns
+		 * the character value (0-255) or -1 if no char available,
+		 * not an SBI error code. Skip the error check for it.
+		 */
+		if (extension_id != SBI_EXT_0_1_CONSOLE_GETCHAR &&
+		    (ret < SBI_LAST_ERR || SBI_SUCCESS < ret)) {
 			sbi_printf("%s: Invalid error %d for ext=0x%lx "
 				   "func=0x%lx\n", __func__, ret,
 				   extension_id, func_id);
